Author of file(s): Ethan Chitturi (CoolestToDoIt)

Comments: Overall, your enemy design is very modular and is a major
improvement from last sprint!! I especially love the use of composition
for enemy movement and attack behaviors! I also love how you have the
FindTarget() method, which will work great for tracking the player or
other IEntities with our ITargetProvider and IPathfindingService interfaces,
once they are implemented in Sprint 5. 

However, there are few things that could be improved:

  1) Bug in AllowedAttackBehaviour.cs: You are using the enemy's velocity 
property to determine attack direction. The "direction != Vector2.Zero" check
means that if the enemy stops moving, it cannot attack. 

  2) Bug in AllowedAttackBehaviour.cs: You are doing "enemy.UpdateAttackTimer(dt)" 
in the Execute() method. If an enemy ever has two attack behaviors, which you do 
have the framework for, the attack timer will be updated twice per frame. This will 
effectively cut the attack cooldown in half.

  3) Bug in ChaseEnemy.cs: You are invoking player.TakeDamage() in 
OnCollision(IPlayer player) regardless of if the attack was actually executed, 
circumventing cooldowns.

  4) As it stands right now, enemies do not add their relevant (StatType, float)
pairs to the inherited EffectStats dictionary. Therefore, they will not be able
to have status effects inflicted on themselves.

Suggested Changes:

  1) Use the targetDirection parameter instead.

  2) Move this update statement into BaseEnemy.Update(). Though, you should 
keep the enemy.ResetAttackTimer() call in AllowedAttackBehaviour.cs.

  3) One potential way to fix this: change IAttackBehaviour.Execute() to return a
bool, indicating whether the attack was actually executed. Then, simply check
if the attack was executed; if it was, invoke player.TakeDamage(); if not, do nothing.

  4) Follow the TODO message in the constructor, and then use the corresponding
EffectStats pairs to actually influence enemy behavior. For example,
EnemyMovingState.HandleMovement() should do 
"_enemy.Velocity = direction * _enemy.GetStat(StatType.MoveSpeed);" when
appropriate.
